%T A395000 0,2,0,1,3,0,1,6,0,2,0,1,0,4,2,0,1,3,0,5,1,0,2,0,1,0,3,1,0,2,0,4,1,0,
%U A395000 2,0,7,1,3,0,1,0,2,0,1,0,5,3,1,0,2,4,0
%N A395000 Sequence generated by the D'Hondt (or Jefferson) apportionment method applied to the geometric distribution with probability mass function p(k) = 1/phi^(k+2) for k >= 0, where phi is the golden ratio.
%C A395000 a(n) is the number k minimizing (c(k)+1)/p(k), where c(k) is the number of occurrences of k among the previous terms. No ties occur because phi^j is irrational for all nonzero integers j.
%C A395000 A003849 is the subsequence of terms equal to 0 or 1.
%C A395000 If the 0's are removed and the remaining terms are decreased by 1, the original sequence is recovered. This is true if we start with any geometric distribution; see A215020 (or A082850) for another example.
%H A395000 Pontus von Brömssen, <a href="/A395000/b395000.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A395000 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%27Hondt_method">D'Hondt method</a>.
%F A395000 Positions of k are given by n_k(m) = Sum_{j>=0} floor(m*phi^(k-j)), m >= 1. (Terms in the series are nonzero only when j <= k+(log m)/(log phi).)
%Y A395000 Cf. A001622, A003849, A020959 (positions of 0's), A082850, A215020, A394854, A395001.
%K A395000 nonn,changed
%O A395000 1,4
%A A395000 _Pontus von Brömssen_, Apr 10 2026
